│ My previous attempts to fix this crash have failed, indicating a deeper misunderstanding of the problem. The core issue is a cyclic dependency between `select`     │
│ instructions that the `dfa-jump-threading` pass does not handle correctly, leading to an assertion failure. My attempts to add local checks for self-reference were │
│ insufficient because the dependency is not a direct self-reference.                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ The problem arises from the pass's recursive nature. When unfolding a `select` (`SI`), it may add one of `SI`'s operands to a worklist if that operand is also a    │
│ `select`. If this new `select` is `SI` itself, an infinite processing loop occurs, which the pass is not equipped to handle, resulting in the `use_empty()`         │
│ assertion failure.                                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ This happens when `unfold` is called on a `select` (`SI`) whose use is a PHI node (`SIUse`), and one of `SI`'s operands is also `SI`. The transformation then tries │
│ to add `SI` back to the worklist to be processed with a *new* PHI node as its use. This creates the infinite loop.                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ The correct fix is to prevent `SI` from being added back to the worklist if it's already the instruction being processed. I will add a check right before the       │
│ `NewSIsToUnfold->push_back` calls. This check will ensure that the `select` being added to the worklist is not the same as the one currently being unfolded.        │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ I will add `if (TrueSI == SI) continue;` (and the equivalent for `FalseSi`) to the `unfold` function. This is the most direct way to break the infinite recursion   │
│ that causes the crash. I will apply this change using `sed`.                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                             │
│ sed -i -e '300i\      if (TrueSI == SI)\n        continue;' -e '302i\      if (FalseSi == SI)\n        continue;' llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/DFAJumpThreading.cpp   │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                 │
